The paper discusses assortative mixing in networks, which is a property often found in social networks. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper also discusses the organization of complex networks, which could fall under cs.SD (Systems and Control), and the measurement of assortativity, which could fall under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) or cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). Finally, the paper introduces a new approach to localize the global measure of assortativity, which could also fall under cs.SOC (Social and Economic Networks).
